t legal status. She introduces us to "suddenly single mothers" who struggle to place food on the table and pay rent after their husbands have been deported. Taking us into the homes and schools of children living in increasingly vulnerable circumstances, she presents families that are divided internally, with some children having legal status while their siblings are undocumented. Even children who are U.S. citizens regularly associate immigration with illegality. With vivid ethnographic details and a striking narrative, Everyday Illegal forces us to confront the devastating impacts of our immigration policies as seen through the eyes of children and their families. As legal status influences identity formation, alters the division of power within families, and affects the opportunities children have outside the home, it becomes a growing source of inequality that ultimately touches us all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of immigrantsxCase studiesxUnited States. 0aChildren of immigrantszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aIllegal aliensxCase studiesxUnited States. 0aIllegal alienszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aIllegal immigrationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aImmigrantsxCase studiesxFamily relationshipsxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxFamily relationshipszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aNoncitizenszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aNoncitizens. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095927940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959279423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959279/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA